'''Néstor Gabriel Lorenzo''' (born 26 February 1966) is an Argentine [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and former player who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]]. He is the current head coach of the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]]. Lorenzo is currently considered to be one of the best national team managers in the world.<ref>https://www.givemesport.com/best-international-football-managers-ranked/</ref>

Lorenzo played for [[Argentinos Juniors]], [[A.S. Bari]], [[Swindon Town]], [[Club Atlético San Lorenzo de Almagro]], [[Ferrocarril Oeste]] and [[Boca Juniors]]. Lorenzo also represented [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] in Italy, including the final which the Argentines lost to [[Germany national football team|Germany]].

==Club career==
Born in [[Villa Celina]], [[La Matanza Partido|La Matanza]], [[Buenos Aires Province]], Lorenzo was a product of [[Argentinos Juniors]]' youth categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/deportes/2024/07/14/fue-subcampeon-del-mundo-con-argentina-y-dirigio-a-scaloni-la-historia-de-nestor-lorenzo-el-dt-que-va-por-la-gloria-en-la-copa-america/|title=Fue subcampeón del mundo con Argentina, dirigió a Scaloni y se lanzó como DT principal recién a los 54 años: Néstor Lorenzo, el DT que va por la gloria con Colombia|trans-title=He was a runner-up of the World Cup with Argentina, managed Scaloni and launched himself as a manager on his own at the age of 54: Néstor Lorenzo, the manager who seeks glory with Colombia|publisher=[[Infobae]]|language=es|date=14 July 2024|accessdate=16 July 2024}}</ref> After making his first team debut in 1985, he spent four seasons at the club before moving to Italian side [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] in 1989.

After ''Italia '90'' and after an attempt by [[Brian Clough]] to sign Lorenzo for [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] fell through, Argentine legend [[Ossie Ardiles]] signed the defender for [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] on loan and eventually the deal became a permanent switch. He played 27 times for The Robins, scoring two goals: one in his debut at the County Ground against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in a 3–0 win, and one away at [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] in a 2–2 draw.

After seeing out his contract, Lorenzo returned to Argentina and signed for [[San Lorenzo de Almagro|San Lorenzo]] in 1992. After two seasons as a starter, he had one-year spells at [[Club Atlético Banfield|Banfield]], [[Ferro Carril Oeste]], [[Boca Juniors]] and [[Primera B Nacional]] side [[Quilmes Atlético Club|Quilmes]], retiring with the latter in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elsolnoticias.com.ar/el-tecnico-finalista-de-colombia-se-retiro-en-quilmes/|title=El técnico finalista de Colombia se retiró en Quilmes|trans-title=The manager finalist with Colombia retired at Quilmes|publisher=El Sol|language=es|date=11 July 2024|accessdate=16 July 2024}}</ref>

==International career==
After featuring in the [[Football at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympics]], Lorenzo made his international debut with the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]] on 6 July 1988, in a 2–2 [[Exhibition match|friendly]] against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]. He was included in [[Carlos Bilardo]]'s 23-man squad for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], featuring in two matches in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup Group B|group stage]] before starting in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup final|final]] against [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ole.com.ar/seleccion/lorenzo-argentina-historia-seleccion_0_EgTWq9qc1i.html|title=La historia de Néstor Lorenzo con la Selección Argentina: jugó un Mundial y fue asistente técnico en otro|trans-title=The story of Néstor Lorenzo with the Argentina national team: played a World Cup and was assistant coach in another one|publisher=[[Olé (sports newspaper)|Olé]]|language=es|date=11 July 2024|accessdate=16 July 2024}}</ref>

==Managerial career==
===Assistant coach===
After retiring, Lorenzo joined [[José Pékerman]]'s staff in the [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina national under-20 team]] in 2000, as an assistant coach. He worked with [[Carlos Aimar]] at Spanish side [[CD Leganés]] under the same role, before reuniting with Pékerman in the Argentina national team in 2004.

Lorenzo remained working with Pékerman at [[Club Toluca|Toluca]], [[Tigres UANL]] and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]].

===Melgar===
On 16 December 2020, Lorenzo had his first managerial experience after being named at the helm of [[Peruvian Primera División]] side [[FBC Melgar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/deporte-total/futbol-peruano/fichajes-melgar-nestor-lorenzo-es-el-nuevo-entrenador-del-cuadro-domino-para-en-el-2021-liga-1-peru-nczd-noticia/|title=Melgar anunció al argentino Néstor Lorenzo como entrenador|trans-title=Melgar announced the Argentine Néstor Lorenzo as manager|publisher=[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]]|language=es|date=16 December 2020|access-date=7 January 2021}}</ref> After a poor start in the [[2021 Liga 1 (Peru)#Fase 1|Fase 1]], as the club finished in the last position of their group, they finished fourth in the [[2021 Liga 1 (Peru)#Fase 2|Fase 2]] and qualified to the [[2022 Copa Sudamericana]].

Under Lorenzo's guidance, Melgar won the [[2022 Liga 1 (Peru)#Torneo Apertura|2022 Apertura tournament]] in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ole.com.ar/futbol-internacional/lorenzo-campeon-melgar-peru_0_t4xvLiIYzL.html|title=Néstor Lorenzo campeón con Melgar|trans-title=Néstor Lorenzo champion with Melgar|publisher=[[Olé (sports newspaper)|Olé]]|language=es|date=3 July 2022|accessdate=16 July 2024}}</ref> He left after qualifying the club to the quarterfinals of the Copa Sudamericana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.uy/futbol/copa-sudamericana/nota/_/id/10605584/melgar-deportivo-cali-nestor-lorenzo-seleccion-colombia|title=Melgar eliminó a Cali y ahora Néstor Lorenzo se dispone a iniciar trabajos con Selección Colombia|trans-title=Melgar knocked out Cali and now Néstor Lorenzo is available to start working with the Colombia national team|publisher=[[ESPN]]|language=es|date=6 July 2022|accessdate=16 July 2024}}</ref>

===Colombia national team===
On 2 June 2022, the [[Colombian Football Federation]] announced Lorenzo as head coach of the national team for the following four years;<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37629018/colombia-hire-nestor-lorenzo-fill-national-team-coaching-vacancy | title=Colombia hire Lorenzo as national team coach | date=3 June 2022 | access-date=23 June 2023 | archive-date=23 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230623161534/https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37629018/colombia-hire-nestor-lorenzo-fill-national-team-coaching-vacancy | url-status=live }}</ref> he remained in charge of Melgar until July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://larepublica.pe/deportes/2022/06/03/nestor-lorenzo-dirigira-a-melgar-hasta-los-octavos-de-la-copa-sudamericana-lrsd/|title=Néstor Lorenzo dirigirá a Melgar hasta los octavos de la Copa Sudamericana|trans-title=Néstor Lorenzo will manage Melgar until the round of 16 of the Copa Sudamericana|publisher=La República|language=Spanish|date=3 June 2022|access-date=3 June 2022}}</ref> On 20 June 2023, Colombia beat the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]] for the first time in its history in a dominant 2–0 victory under Lorenzo.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/visitors-colombia-stun-germany-2-0-latest-setback-euro-2024-hosts-2023-06-20/ | title=Colombia stun Germany 2-0 in latest setback for Euro 2024 hosts | newspaper=Reuters | date=20 June 2023 | access-date=23 June 2023 | archive-date=23 June 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230623161535/https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/visitors-colombia-stun-germany-2-0-latest-setback-euro-2024-hosts-2023-06-20/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2024, Colombia went 28 games undefeated under Lorenzo and had significant victories over the national teams of Germany, [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] and [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rpctv.com/futbol/futbol-internacional/copa-america-2024/copa-america-2024-nestor-lorenzo-y-una-colombia-que-acumula-28-partidos-invicto-n5996862|title=Copa América 2024: Néstor Lorenzo y una Colombia que acumula 28 partidos invicto|trans-title=2024 Copa América: Néstor Lorenzo and a Colombia which reaches 28 matches unbeaten|publisher=[[RPC Televisión]]|language=es|date=11 July 2024|accessdate=16 July 2024}}</ref> Another major achievement of Lorenzo's was leading the national team to its [[2024 Copa América final|first Copa America final]] in 23 years and managing Colombia to score 12 goals in the 2024 Copa America, their highest record in the competition;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/751459-lo-que-tiene-y-lo-que-le-falta-a-colombia-para-ganar-la-fina|title=Lo que tiene y lo que le falta a Colombia para ganar la final|trans-title=What Colombia has and what Colombia lacks to win the final|publisher=[[Página 12]]|language=es|date=12 July 2024|accessdate=16 July 2024}}</ref> they lost the final on extra time to Argentina. In September 2025, Colombia qualified for the 2026 FIFA World Cup under Lorenzo, finishing third in CONMEBOL and achieving the nation’s seventh World Cup qualification.

